  "prompt": "Where is the RAW filter in Photoshop CS6?",
  "response": "In Photoshop CS6, the Camera Raw filter is not available as a separate filter within the Filter menu. Instead, Camera Raw functions as a plugin editor. To access Camera Raw in Photoshop CS6, you typically open a RAW file directly. Here's how you can access and use Camera Raw:\n\n1. **Open a RAW File**: When you open a RAW image file (.CR2, .NEF, etc.) directly in Photoshop CS6, it automatically launches Camera Raw for editing.\n\n2. **Smart Objects**: If you want to apply Camera Raw adjustments to a non-RAW image (like a JPEG or TIFF), you can do this by converting the image layer into a Smart Object. Once you have a Smart Object, you can go to the menu `Filter > Camera Raw Filter`. However, note that the Camera Raw Filter directly in the Filter menu was introduced in Photoshop CC, not CS6.\n\n3. **Bridge**: You can also open JPEGs or TIFFs in Camera Raw via Adobe Bridge. Right-click on an image and select \"Open in Camera Raw.\"\n\nIf you frequently work with non-RAW images and need Camera Raw functionalities, using Adobe Bridge or converting your layer to a Smart Object are your primary options in CS6.",
